<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
We describe 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. valerieae" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="valerieae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">P. valerieae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from a single male based on our observations of interspecific, intraspecific, and intersexual variation within the genus. The coloration of all 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Platygastridae" genus="Pulchrisolia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pulchrisolia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Pulchrisolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species known from males and females is virtually identical, with slight differences having been observed on the head (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 17–21" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 17 - 21. Pulchrisolia diehoekensis, female holotype (SAM-HYM-P 038987) 17 head, mesosoma, T 1, T 2, dorsal view 18 head, mesosoma, S 1, lateral view 19 head, anterior view 20 male paratype (SAM-HYM-P 038989), head, mesosoma, metasoma, dorsal view 21 head, anterior view. Scale bars in millimeters." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.73.33876.figures17-21" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/355936" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" tableDoi="10.3897/jhr.73.33876.figures17-21">Figures 19</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 17–21" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 17 - 21. Pulchrisolia diehoekensis, female holotype (SAM-HYM-P 038987) 17 head, mesosoma, T 1, T 2, dorsal view 18 head, mesosoma, S 1, lateral view 19 head, anterior view 20 male paratype (SAM-HYM-P 038989), head, mesosoma, metasoma, dorsal view 21 head, anterior view. Scale bars in millimeters." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.73.33876.figures17-21" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/355936" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" tableDoi="10.3897/jhr.73.33876.figures17-21">21</figureCitation>
) and mesoscutum (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 5. Pulchrisolia teras, male (CASENT 2043867), head, mesosoma, T 1, dorsal view. Scale bar in millimeters." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.73.33876.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/355933" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" tableDoi="10.3897/jhr.73.33876.figure5">Figures 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 50" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 50. Pulchrisolia teras, female holotype (CASENT 2043862) 50 head, mesosoma, T 1, T 2, dorsal view. Scale bar in millimeters." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.73.33876.figure50" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/355944" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" tableDoi="10.3897/jhr.73.33876.figure50">50</figureCitation>
) of certain species. Most species in the genus are light yellow, orange, or dark red in color; however, the male of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. valerieae" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="valerieae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">P. valerieae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has most of its mesosoma, and portions of its metasoma and legs, brownish-black (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 65–70" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figures 65 - 70. Pulchrisolia valerieae, male holotype (BMNH 010823075) 65 head, mesosoma, metasoma, dorsal view 66 mesosoma, dorsal view 67 head, mesosoma, metasoma, lateral view 68 mesosoma, lateral view 69 head, anterior view 70 metasoma, dorsal view. Scale bars in millimeters." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.73.33876.figures65-70" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/355949" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" tableDoi="10.3897/jhr.73.33876.figures65-70">Figures 65-68</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 65–70" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figures 65 - 70. Pulchrisolia valerieae, male holotype (BMNH 010823075) 65 head, mesosoma, metasoma, dorsal view 66 mesosoma, dorsal view 67 head, mesosoma, metasoma, lateral view 68 mesosoma, lateral view 69 head, anterior view 70 metasoma, dorsal view. Scale bars in millimeters." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.73.33876.figures65-70" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/355949" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" tableDoi="10.3897/jhr.73.33876.figures65-70">70</figureCitation>
). The only other species that approximates the coloration of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. valerieae" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="valerieae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">P. valerieae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. teras" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="teras">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">P. teras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but this species has notauli and the antero-admedian depression is prominent and hemispherical in shape, even in smaller specimens. Based on what we have observed in other species of the genus, we expect both male and female 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. valerieae" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="valerieae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">P. valerieae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to share similar coloration patterns and possess antero-admedian lines that flank a shallow antero-admedian depression of similar size, making it unlikely that the holotype male is conspecific with 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. maculata" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">P. maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or any of the newly described species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Platygastridae" genus="Pulchrisolia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pulchrisolia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Pulchrisolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known only from females.
</paragraph>
